Our most significant set of findings is shown in Fig. 3. We calculate the partial coherence between carbon risk and green and renewable energy. The information about the size of the effect that a shock in one indicator will impact on the other will be dominated by the partial phase difference and the partial wavelet gain. Our paper displays these values of the three frequency bands under consideration, namely, for cycles of period 8–32 days and 34–68 days, and relating to the linkage between the S&P green bond index, S&P global clean energy index, and carbon emission futures and relating to cycles of period 6–48 days and 48–130 days for the linkage between clean energy and carbon emission futures, respectively. The mean is calculated as a circular mean for the phase-differences evaluated on a circular scale; this is the accepted definition of mean in this situation. In Figs. 3 and 4, we show partial wavelet coherency between these indicators. The partial coherency between S&P green bond and carbon emission futures is seen in Panel A of Fig. 3. Significant low coherency zones coincide with those shown in Fig. 2 as low coherencies. The majority of the regions spanned from the beginning of the sample to early 2018 and were in the 48–130 frequency range. Other regions spanned from the beginning of 2020 to the end of 2021 and were positioned at low frequencies (48–130-day period). The phase difference in these areas can be divided into two phases. The phases (from early 2017 to early 2018 and from early 2020 to the end of 2021) range from -π2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
